With over 170 species distributed across the tropics and subtropics worldwide and 47 nominate species occurring in India , the genus Hemidactylus is one of the most speciose gekkonid genera (
Uetz et al. 2021
). Increased interest in and research into this group has led to many new species descriptions, taxonomic revisions, and distribution extensions (Giri 2008; Giri & Bauer 2008 ;
Giri et al . 2009
; Mahony 2009 , 2011 ;
Gaikwad et al. 2010
;
Purkayastha et al. 2010
; Ganesh & Chandramouli 2010 ;
Agarwal et al . 2011
;
Bauer et al . 2012
;
Pal et al. 2013
;
Srinivasulu et al . 2014
; Mirza & Sanap 2014 ;
Kumar et al. 2015
;
Murthy et al. 2015
; Mirza & Raju 2017 ;
Ganesh et al. 2017
;
Agarwal et al. 2018
;
Chaitanya et al. 2018
;
Mirza et al. 2018
;
Srikanthan et al. 2018
;
Agarwal et al. 2019
;
Khandekar et al. 2020a
; Lajmi et al. 2020). With the advancement of molecular phylogenetics over the past decade, our understanding of radiations and relationships within Indian Hemidactylus and the detection of cryptic species have increased substantially ( Bansal & Karanth 2010 , 2013 ;
Bauer et al. 2010a
, b;
Lajmi et al. 2016
, 2019;
Chaitanya et al. 2019
;
Agarwal et al. 2020a
).

Indian hemidactyls are part of a tropical Asian radiation, and consist of five major branches—the Hemidactylus prashadi , H. flaviviridis , H. brookii , H. frenatus , and H. platyurus groups ( Bansal & Karanth 2010 , 2013 ;
Lajmi et al. 2016
). Hemidactylus giganteus sensu lato is a member of the H. flaviviridis group, and sister to H. flaviviridis Rüppell
, H. leschenaultii Duméril & Bibron
, H. hemchandrai Dandge & Tiple
, and H. yajurvedi Murthy et al. ( Bansal & Karanth 2010 ;
Lajmi et al. 2019
). It was first described by F. Stoliczka in the late 19 th century based on a series of specimens collected by W. T . Blanford “on the Godávári river near Badráchalam [Bhadrachalam, Telangana State], on trees’’ ( Stoliczka 1871 , 1872 ) (
). In the original description, Stoliczka presumed this species to be similar to Hemidactylus flaviviridis ( H. coctaei Duméril & Bibron
= H. bengaliensis Anderson
) but much larger in size, equal to Gecko guttatus
Daudin [= Gekko gecko (Linnaeus)
]. The brief description of the type series was summarized as “ first labial not entering the nostril, 18–20 femoral pores on either side of thigh, separate in praeanal region; olive grey, marbled and spotted with darker ”. More than a century later,
Giri et al. (2003)
redescribed the species without consulting the type series, or basing it on topotypes, and opined that there is wide variability within the known specimens of H. giganteus .

As per literature, the range of H. giganteus is throughout most of peninsular India ( Srinivasulu & Srinivasulu 2013 ;
Srinivasulu et al. 2014
), however it is relatively poorly researched. The description of H. yajurvedi and H. hemchandrai in 2015, two cryptic species found within the range of H. giganteus , suggested the possible existence of other cryptic diversity within this taxon. Furthermore, the limited original description of H. giganteus is inadequate and, as a result, the existing diagnosis of the species sensu stricto cannot unambiguously differentiate among members of the more extensive complex, as now understood. In this paper, we provide a detailed description of H. giganteus sensu stricto based on series of specimens collected from the type locality, and discuss variation within H. giganteus sensu lato from the known range, and describe three cryptic species previously assigned to H. giganteus from Telangana and Karnataka states based on morphological and phylogenetic analyses.

Sampling and study area. Multiple field surveys were carried out in South India between September 2015 and February 2017 at 68 localities in 24 districts of Telangana State and two localities (Hampi, Bellary District and Raichur, Raichur District) in Karnataka State , broadly covering the distribution of H. giganteus sensu lato . Specific surveys were conducted at the type locality of Hemidactylus giganteus sensu stricto (Bhadrachalam, Telangana State), to study and collect topotypes. Voucher specimens were preserved following standard procedures (
Ceríaco et al. 2020
). Sampling was carried out during peak activity times for geckos, between 1830–2100hrs. During the surveys, sites were checked by two to three persons with the aid of a flashlight, photographs of live specimens encountered were taken, and vouchers were collected.

Sequences of other species in the greater Hemidactylus flaviviridis branch, including those of H. flaviviridis , H. leschenaultii , H. hemchandrai , and H. yajurvedi were aligned with sequences of members of H. giganteus sensu lato , retrieved from the NCBI GenBank database ( Table 1 ). H. frenatus was used as an outgroup, following the phylogeny described by Lajmi & Karanth (2020) . The generated and retrieved sequences were aligned using MUSCLE ( Edgar 2004 ) integrated in MEGA 6 (
Tamura et al. 2013
). The best-fit nucleotide substitution model was tested using JModelTest2 (
Darriba et al. 2012
) based on the optimal Bayesian Information Criterion (BIC)—Hasegawa-Kishino-Yano model with 4 discrete Gamma categories (HKY+G4;
Hasegawa et al. 1985
) was the best-fit model for the analysis. Bayesian inference, conducted in BEAST 1.10.4 (
Suchard et al. 2018
) was used to recover the phylogeny, separating the taxa by ingroup and outgroup. The program was run for 10 million generations sampling every 1000 generations, and the first 20% of trees were discarded as burn-in. The inference was generated under a relaxed uncorrelated lognormal clock model, and a Yule speciation-based tree model. Quality of inference was checked using Tracer v1.6 (
Rambaut et al. 2014
), by assessing ESS values (to be>200 for all priors), and a majorityrule consensus tree was generated using TreeAnnotator 1.10.4, included in the BEAST 1.10.4 package. Uncorrected p-distance was calculated in MEGA 6.

To infer putative species within the H. flaviviridis complex, we used species delimitation based on the Bayesian Poisson Tree Process (bPTP), implemented on the Species Delimitation web server (http://species.h-its.org/ptp/;
Zhang et al. 2013
), excluding the outgroup taxon to optimise the process. The analysis was run for 100,000 generations with a thinning parameter of 100 and a burnin of 0.25.

