sec.p:
Studies on herpetofauna in peninsular India have historically been restricted to the Western Ghats biodiversity hotspot ( Hutton & David 2009 ;
Ganesh et al. 2014
). Other much drier and more arid ecoregions including the Eastern Ghats and the Deccan plateau have been less explored ( Srinivasulu & Das 2008 ;
Ganesh et al. 2017
;
Lajmi et al. 2019
), and with increased interest in such areas, in the recent past many new taxa of reptiles have been discovered and described from here. Research focusing on the arid rocky hinterlands of the Deccan plateau—especially the Karnataka and Telangana plateaus—has revealed notable cryptic diversity in hemidactyls ( Mahony 2009 ;
Srinivasulu et al. 2018
; Lajmi et al. 2020) and other lizards (
Srinivasulu et al. 2015
;
Deepak et al. 2018
; Agarwal et al. 2020b;
Khandekar et al. 2020b
), and has highlighted the need for focused research into historically understudied taxa. One such taxon is Hemidactylus giganteus sensu lato , which shows large variations in the number of femoral pores on either thigh and poreless scales separating them—a major diagnostic character in hemidactyls. To study the variants within this taxon for their systematic significance, we critically examined the forms assumed to be H. giganteus in its known range.

Due to the lack of a detailed type description and convincing differential diagnosis, the relationship between H. giganteus sensu stricto from its type locality—Bhadrachalam (Telangana State, India ), and forms of H. giganteus complex from other parts of India is not precisely defined. We addressed this issue by providing the first clear systematic diagnosis and description for this species based on syntypes and topotypes. Taxa belonging to Hemidactylus giganteus sensu lato are members of the tropical Asian branch of the H. flaviviridis group, which comprises H. flaviviridis and its congeners including H. leschenaultii , H. giganteus sensu lato , H. hemchandrai , and H. yajurvedi . The discovery of the latter two species highlighted the presence of marked cryptic diversity within this species group.
Giri et al. (2003)
noted that H. giganteus sensu lato is highly variable, recommending in-depth study to resolve the systematic status of populations of large-bodied hemidactyl geckos loosely assigned to H. giganteus sensu lato . We discovered three cryptic species within this group— Hemidactylus raya sp. nov. , Hemidactylus saxicolus sp. nov. , and Hemidactylus aemulus sp. nov. , all found within the known range of H. giganteus sensu lato on the Karnataka and Telangana plateaus. We also recovered three additional putative new species [indicated as Sp1, Sp2, and Sp3], which were included as H. giganteus in earlier studies [see Bansal & Karanth (2010) and Lajmi & Karanth (2020) ], and are awaiting description. The detection of the cryptic species is based on molecular phylogenetics and genetic species delimitation, a suite of techniques increasingly employed to resolve cryptic species diversity in many taxa, as evident from the recent discoveries and taxonomic reassessments of hemidactyls in peninsular India ( Bansal & Karanth 2010 , 2013 ;
Bauer et al. 2010a
, b;
Murthy et al. 2015
;
Lajmi et al. 2016
;
Giri et al. 2017
;
Srinivasulu et al. 2018
; Mirza 2018). However, the taxonomic status of some populations assigned to H . cf. giganteus from Andhra Pradesh , Maharashtra , Tamil Nadu , and Kerala , for which sequences are unavailable remains unresolved.

H. giganteus sensu lato is a widely distributed species group, and has been recorded from Andhra Pradesh , Kerala , Tamil Nadu , and Telangana State (
Giri et al. 2003
; Giri 2008; Srinivasulu & Srinivasulu 2013 ;
Srinivasulu et al. 2014
). With the description of H. yajurvedi by
Murthy et al. (2015)
, records of H. giganteus from Chhattisgarh (vide Sanyal & Dasgupta 1990 ; Chandra & Gajbe 2005 ) no longer apply to this species. In Maharashtra , the historic reports of H. giganteus from Pandava Caves and Ozar in Nasik District by Soman (1966) and Chopra (1968) are assigned to H. aaronbaueri (
Pal et al. 2013
)
. The five specimens ( BNHS 1259/1–4 and BNHS 1590) housed in the collections of the BNHS from Sironcha, Gadchiroli District, and Yawal Wildlife Sanctuary, Jalgaon District ( Maharashtra , India ) (
Giri et al . 2003
) are similar in meristics to H. raya sp. nov. Sironcha is within the area of overlap of the distributions of H. giganteus and H. yajurvedi , indicating sympatry between these species and H. raya sp. nov. The taxonomic status of H. cf. giganteus from Chandrapur ( Maharashtra , India ) needs to be resolved. We also emphasize the need to study the geographic boundaries of these species’ ranges, to confirm sympatry between species with overlapping distributions.
